/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:11:### Step 1 - Freeze the endpoint, baseline criterion, and anti-conjugation rule
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:13:This step is under-specified in exactly the place where the entire chain gets its objectivity. "Choose one inherited theorem-facing endpoint" is too loose. There are several plausible endpoints on the LEI/CKN floor, and the choice of endpoint already biases which reformulations can look useful. If the endpoint is picked before seeing any candidate behavior, the chain may overconstrain the search. If it is picked after informal exposure to candidates, the chain becomes selection-biased while pretending not to be.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:19:The kill condition is also too aggressive. "If no single endpoint and burden currency can be frozen before algebra begins, stop" mistakes setup ambiguity for mathematical failure. In a program whose whole point is to test whether a reformulation changes the mechanism, some controlled ambiguity at the start is normal. Killing the route here risks screening out the few ideas that only become intelligible once the exact equation is on the page.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:25:The requirement to derive the "full exact equation" is strong in principle, but it smuggles in a huge cost without saying what level of exactness matters for the endpoint. Some debts only appear after localization, truncation, or pressure splitting. A full-space exact evolution can look cleaner than the localized argument it is supposed to serve. So this step risks certifying algebraic exactness while missing the real place where the route dies.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:37:Keeping at most one promoted candidate and one backup is also too aggressive for this stage. If the mission is wide-funnel planning, then Step 3 should compare a small handful of candidates against the same burden ledger. Otherwise the chain can confuse "first candidate that cleared a vague threshold" with "best available candidate."
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:43:This is where the chain tries to become honest, and it is also where it is weakest. "Write one explicit localization or contradiction line" understates the complexity of endpoint insertion. LEI/CKN arguments do not usually hinge on a single line; they depend on a tightly coupled stack of local energy, pressure decomposition, scaling, covering, and compactness. A candidate that helps one displayed line can still fail because it wrecks admissibility or cannot be threaded through the rest of the proof skeleton.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:47:The rejection rule, "reject candidates that improve a local surrogate while the full endpoint burden returns unchanged," is fair in spirit but vulnerable to overreach. Some viable programs work by improving a surrogate that is not itself the theorem-facing burden but that changes the induction, compactness, or contradiction architecture downstream. This step treats non-immediate transfer as evidence of failure, which biases toward only those routes whose payoff is almost already theorem-shaped.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:49:The kill condition is probably necessary, but only if the insertion test is genuinely full-strength. As written, it is not. So the chain risks claiming "endpoint-transfer obstruction" on the basis of an insertion model that is thinner than the actual endpoint argument.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:63:The final classification also compresses too much. "Anti-conjugation collapse," "non-coercivity," "endpoint-transfer failure," and "Tao-insensitive packaging" are useful labels, but they are not fine enough to guide the next iteration unless each is tied to a specific failed term, estimate, or incompatibility. Otherwise the endpoint is a neat label, not a sharpened obstruction.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:70:- It is heavily path-dependent. Freezing one endpoint early and one candidate family early can manufacture failure or success depending on initial framing rather than mathematical substance.
/Users/seanross/kingdom_of_god/building_models/current_hunts/big-thinkers/codex-philosopher-atlas/missions/beyond-de-giorgi/planning-runs/run-009/attacks/chain-01.md:72:- It conflates exact reformulation with proof-relevant reformulation. Exactness matters, but exactness is cheap compared with endpoint leverage. The chain knows this in words, but its early steps still spend too much effort certifying exactness before demanding proof-scale consequences.
